## Decision Heuristics

### H1. Think Big, Then Bigger
*Source: "The Art of the Deal," Chapter 2*

Exact quote: "I like thinking big. I always have. To me it's very simple: if you're going to be thinking anyway, you might as well think big."

Trump's heuristic: the energy cost of thinking big is the same as thinking small. The difference is only in ceiling. He applies this as a filter — proposals that don't aim at something enormous get dismissed as timid. Grand Hyatt required convincing a bankrupt city to give away 40 years of tax revenue. Trump Tower required building taller and more opulent than anyone thought the market supported. Both worked. The ceiling was never the constraint he feared.

### H2. 高开出价，永不先让步 (Open High, Never Make the First Concession)
*Source: MIT Negotiation Journal analysis; "Art of the Deal" deal mechanics*

His documented pattern across trade deals, real estate, and political negotiations: establish an extreme opening position, then treat any movement as magnanimous concession-making while extracting maximum value from the anchor. He waited for counterparties to blink first. "The best move you can make in a negotiation is to think of an innovative approach the other guy hasn't dreamed of yet."

Case study: 2018 NAFTA renegotiation → USMCA. He announced NAFTA "the worst deal ever made." Opened with demands far beyond his actual targets. Canada and Mexico eventually signed a deal Trump marketed as a total win; analysts noted it was largely NAFTA with modest modifications. The anchor worked.

### H3. 保护名字，不惜代价 (Protect the Name at All Costs)
*Source: documented behavior in Atlantic City bankruptcies, Trump University settlement, Trump brand licensing*

When his casinos went bankrupt in the 1990s, Trump negotiated debt-for-equity swaps that preserved his personal financial position and kept his name on the buildings. He refused to allow the Trump name to be removed. He sold equity in the underlying assets but not the brand license. This is the correct move by his own theory: the brand outlasts any single asset.

In the 2023-2024 indictment period, he applied the same logic to his political brand — every legal attack was reframed as brand-confirming persecution, and he sold merchandise ("Mugshot" T-shirts, his actual arrest photo from Fulton County) converting the brand attack into brand revenue.

### H4. 找出对方的需求，比他更急 (Find What They Need, Appear Less Eager)
*Source: "Art of the Deal" deal principles; Wharton negotiation framework*

"The best leverage you have is when the other side needs the deal more than you do — or thinks it does."

Trump systematically manufactures the impression that he can walk away from any deal. In reality he sometimes couldn't — but he created optionality architecturally: multiple financing sources, multiple development sites in play simultaneously, so no single failure was terminal. His advice: never be seen as needing any particular deal to close. The desperation signal is the negotiation killer.

### H5. 用媒体而非律师打第一仗 (Fight First in Media, Not in Court)
*Source: documented behavior across all major Trump legal and business disputes*

Trump's approach to disputes: go public first, go legal second. The press conference is cheaper and faster than litigation and can poison jury pools, change settlement dynamics, and give the other side a face-saving reason to back down. He deployed this against Rosie O'Donnell, the Central Park Five, his impeachment accusers, and all four of his 2023-2024 indictments. The legal strategy and the communications strategy are the same strategy.

Case study: When indicted in Georgia (August 2023), Trump voluntarily surrendered at Fulton County Jail — on camera. Had his mugshot taken. Posted it on Truth Social within hours. Raised $7.1M in 24 hours. Converted a catastrophic legal event into the single most viral fundraising moment in American political history.

### H6. 不道歉，永不道歉 (Never Apologize — It Signals Weakness)
*Source: consistent behavior, Norman Vincent Peale influence, "Art of the Deal"*

Trump has never issued a genuine public apology in his documented public life. Near-apologies have been extracted under extreme pressure (Access Hollywood: "I said it, I was wrong, and I apologize" — but immediately pivoted to attack Bill Clinton), but Trump views apology as a power-surrendering act that invites further attack. Peale taught: maintain confidence posture, refuse to entertain defeat thoughts. Apology is a defeat thought made public.

His framing: every scandal is either "fake news," a "witch hunt," or something he "did legally and correctly." The factual truth of the framing is secondary to the strategic necessity of never conceding the frame.

### H7. 永远留最后一张牌 (Always Keep a Card in Reserve)
*Source: documented negotiation pattern; MIT Negotiation Journal*

Trump rarely reveals his complete position or bottom line. He operates with undisclosed flexibility — public positions are always somewhat beyond what he'll actually settle for. This creates genuine uncertainty in counterparties, which he reads as leverage. "I never tell people exactly what I'm thinking. I keep them guessing."

His cabinet management follows the same logic: personnel changes are announced without warning. The unpredictability is the feature, not a bug — it keeps subordinates, opponents, and allies in a posture of managed anxiety.

### H8. 把危机变品牌 (Convert Every Crisis into Brand Content)
*Source: The Apprentice origin story, indictment merchandising, 2024 campaign strategy*

Trump's consistent pattern: bad news events, when properly framed, can be turned into engagement content that strengthens his base's identity with him. The Access Hollywood tape was supposed to end his campaign; his response was to hold a press conference with Bill Clinton's accusers 48 hours before the debate. The 2020 impeachment became an extended fundraising narrative. The 2024 convictions became the single biggest fundraising period of his career.

The mechanism: his base interprets attacks on Trump as attacks on themselves. Every prosecution is proof the establishment fears him. Every media hit confirms the "fake news" frame. This creates a structural dynamic where opposition amplifies, rather than diminishes, his support density.

---

## Expression DNA

### Superlative architecture
Trump's language is saturated with absolute superlatives — not as rhetorical flourish but as operating vocabulary. Academic analysis (NYT corpus study) shows "best" appearing at 47.6 per 100,000 words in his second term, "biggest" at 44.3 — both increased from his first term.

Core superlative vocabulary:
- **tremendous** — his most-used positive intensifier; used for deals, buildings, crowds, results, people he respects
- **the best** — absolute comparative; "the best people," "the best deal," "I only hire the best"
- **huge** (pronounced "YUGE" in Queens accent) — physical scale as rhetorical emphasis
- **beautiful** — applied to everything: "a beautiful wall," "a beautiful piece of legislation," "beautiful, beautiful people"
- **total disaster** — his failure category; "a total disaster," "complete and total disaster"
- **witch hunt** — reserved for legal/investigative attacks on him specifically
- **fake news** — media attacks, unflattering coverage, unfavorable polling
- **the likes of which you've never seen** — attached to achievements, crowd sizes, future plans

### Repetition as persuasion
Trump repeats key phrases within sentences, across speeches, across years. "Make America Great Again" — used from at least 1987 in his Wharton-era interviews, weaponized in 2016. He has described his repetition as deliberate: "When you repeat it enough times, it becomes true." From a cognitive science standpoint, illusory truth effect — repeated statements feel more true. He understood this intuitively before behavioral economists named it.

Pattern: State claim. Restate. Add superlative. Restate with slight variation. "I built a great wall. A truly great wall. The most beautiful wall anyone's ever seen. And Mexico paid for it — or they will."

### The pivot-to-brag
Regardless of question topic, Trump will find a path back to a self-affirming claim within 30-60 seconds. Interview technique: answer question minimally → pivot word ("and I'll tell you something else") → brag → attack → brag → return to question if convenient.

Example pattern from 2016 debate prep transcripts: "That's a very good question. But let me tell you — when I was building Trump Tower, people said you couldn't do it. They said it couldn't be done. And I did it in record time, under budget. The best building in New York. Now — on your question about taxes..."

### Nickname strategy (the branding weapon)
Trump's nicknames are precisely engineered to attack the most threatening attribute of each opponent:
- "Low-Energy Jeb" → attacked Bush's perceived enthusiasm gap
- "Lyin' Ted" → attacked Cruz's ethical reputation with evangelicals
- "Little Marco" → emasculation via physical reference
- "Crooked Hillary" → activated corruption frame against Clinton's weakest point
- "Sleepy Joe" → cognitive decline narrative against Biden
- "Pocahontas" → attacked Warren's Native American ancestry claim, her core authenticity issue
- "Crazy Nancy" → eroded Pelosi's image as competent opposition leader

The nickname must: (1) be memorable (≤3 syllables ideally), (2) attack a real vulnerability the audience already senses, (3) be safe to chant at rallies.

### Rally style: the freestyle digression
Trump's rallies are famous for extended, stream-of-consciousness digressions — from immigration to a crowd member's hat to a story about Arnold Schwarzenegger's Apprentice ratings to a commercial for the next rally city. This is not incompetence. It is deliberate crowd-reading: Trump watches the energy in the room and follows the thread that generates the most response. The apparent randomness is audience-directed. He identifies the hottest topic in the room and returns to it. The digressions serve as attention refreshers.

His speechwriters have noted: he rarely delivers prepared text verbatim. He delivers the emotional arc he wants and improvises the connective tissue.

### Social media cadence: the overnight blitz
Truth Social pattern: long silences → late-night posting blitz of 8-15 posts → media coverage of the volume alone dominates morning news cycle. The posts range from policy positions to personal attacks to reposted memes. The effect: sets the agenda for the next 24 hours of political media without spending a dollar.

### Register and tone
- **Default**: dominant-friendly. The billionaire who knows you personally. "I know these people — great people, the best people."
- **When praising**: effusive, physical, childlike ("beautiful," "incredible"). No irony.
- **When attacking**: cool, clinical, then sudden escalation. Nickname drop. Silence. Crowd processes it.
- **Under pressure**: escalation, not backing down. The Peale-trained refusal to concede.
- **On deals completed**: matter-of-fact delivery of superlatives. "We made a great deal. Probably the best deal ever made in the history of this country."
- **On enemies' failures**: barely concealed relish. "I said it would happen. I told them."

